}
\section{Scaling Ironwood}{
    \p{\strong{Torus Cube}:}
    \ul{
      \li{64 ironwood chips}
      \li{Each chip connects to 6 neighbors via high-speed Inter-Chip Interconnect}
      \li{Form a 3d torus, providing three axes for parallel bandwidth.}
    }
    \p{\strong{Optical Circuit Switching}:}
    \ul{
      \li{Multiple cubes are linked by an OCS network to build pods.}
      \li{If a cube fails, the OCS optically bypasses and swaps in a spare.}
      \li{OCS allows for slices without system shutdown (?)}
    }
}
}
\transclude{NZZ7}
\section{XLA Compilation}{
\p{\strong{Overview:}}
\ul{
  \li{Dispatch / Cache: caches compilation based on input argument signatures i.e. shapes, dtypes, sharding. If shapes change will need to \strong{recompile}.}
  \li{XLA transformation: Python -> JaxPR -> StableHLO, performing fusion and other simplifications to reduce memory overhead (?).}
  \li{TPU specific: Further reduced to LLO IR, then \em{very large instruction word} (VLIW) scheduling to map dot products to MXU.}
}
\remark{
As soon as python code is traced into jaxpr it is thrown away. Only HLO is input to XLA compiler.
}
\p{\strong{Compilation (Pipeline):}}
\ol{
  \li{Tracing: Python / JAX -> Jaxpr}
  \ul{
    \li{\code{jax.make_jaxpr(fun)(*args)}}
    \li{Abstract execution. JAX executes python code using abstract tracer objects instead of real arrays.}
    \li{Recording the FLow. Every operation and its intermediate result is recorded into JAXpr.}
    \li{Sequence used to construct a grap, which the XLA compiler will later optimize.}
    \li{Python code is executed once during tracing but excluded from final graph.}
    \li{Each JAX primitive registers functions for}
    \ul{
        \li{Lowering to StableHLO}  
        \li{How it is transformed under \code{grad} and \code{vmap}.}
    }
  }
  \li{Lowering: Jaxpr -> HLO}
  \ul{
    \li{\code{fn_lowered = jax.jit(fun).lower(*args)}}
    \li{\code{stable_hlo = fn_lowered.as_text()}}
    \li{\code{hlo = fn_lowered.compiler_ir('hlo')}}
    \li{Multiple ML frameworks lower to StableHLO.}
    \ul{
      \li{Hardware agnostic.}
      \li{Backwards compatible.}
    }
  }
  \li{Compile: HLO -> Optimized HLO -> LLO IR -> VLIW -> Executables}
  \ul{
    \li{\code{compiled = fn_lowered.compile()}}
    \li{\code{compiled.runtime_executable()} returns a \code{LoadedExecutable}.}
    \li{Useful(?) \code{compiled.cost_analysis()}.}
    \li{HLO:}
    \ul{
      \li{Input for XLA compiler.}
      \li{Directed acyclic graph of copmutational operations.}
      \li{All array dimensions are known at compile time.}
      \li{Limited opcodes i.e. Add, Multiply, Transpose, Dot, etc.}
    }
  }
}
\p{\strong{XLA Shapes and Memory Layout}}
\ul{
  \li{Every data type defined by data type and fixed dimensions, determined at compile time.}
  \li{Minor-to-major order i.e. fastest changing to slowesting changin.}
  \li{Tiling: arrays are split into smaller blocks to fit into VREG. Want to arrange data to efficiently fit VREG.}
}
\figure{
\<html:img>[width]{60\%}[src]{\route-asset{assets/img/xla-mem-layout.png}}{}
\figcaption{How memory is laid out based on XLA.}
}
\p{\strong{Execution:}}
\ul{
  \li{Move tensors from CPU to HBM. Sharding is taken care of by PJIT if on TPU pod.}
  \li{Async: Immediately returns a \code{Future} JAX array while the hardware executes VLIW microcode asynchronously.}
  \li{Buffer management: Returns pointer to TPU memory. All handled lazily. Not copied back to CPU until \code{jax.block_until_ready()}.}
}

}
